The play "Twelfth Night" seems to suggest that while disguise can indeed be useful in sustaining prolonged deception, ultimately, one must discard that newly adopted guise, or risk losing oneself forever in the process. One significant challenge in ending a deception, however, is that one may find themselves alienated in the aftermath. Therefore, ultimately, one must choose between self-preservation or maintaining relationships with those around them. Although some may respond neutrally to discovering that they have been deceived, others may take such deception very seriously and become offended by the whole charade.
The topic of deception in gender role reversal is especially problematic because it raises numerous side issues, with the most significant being why? Why do subjects feel the need to shirk their own identity and adopt a disguise in the form of the opposite gender? In Viola's case, it is clearly a form of self-protection: "I'll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…" (5.1.247-249)
Having newly arrived in a foreign land, Viola feels compelled to pretend to be a man to protect herself from potential attackers. Viola's plan works, but it also isolates her from the women around her, cutting her off from an essential support system. To make matters worse, she is so convincing as a man that Olivia mistakes her for Sebastian and falls in love with her: "Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay." (5.1.138) Furthermore, she must also deal with suppressed romantic feelings between her and Orsino: "Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me." (5.1.260-261)
While this may be a somewhat progressive stance, to a modern reader, "Twelfth Night" might be seen as an illustration of how deception can facilitate the revelation of suppressed emotions, especially in the cases of Olivia and Orsino. Certain passages seem to suggest that these characters may have unexpressed subconscious desires that Viola/Cesario's appearance forces them to confront. For instance, is Olivia attracted to Cesario because Cesario appears to be a man, or does Olivia secretly harbor feelings for women? One could argue that this is unlikely, as Shakespeare's character Olivia seems more likely to parody the people of his time who judge others solely based on their appearance.
This is evident in how Olivia easily switches her affections from Cesario to Sebastian and begins to regard Cesario/Viola as family rather than a love interest: "A sister, you are she." (5.1.315)

Germany's colonial rule has been widely noted for its brutality, particularly in its treatment of the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. It's clear that no colonial empire can be summarized by such a single description. The German colonial empire was as diverse in its policies and governance styles as it was in its geography. Educational provision throughout the colonies was also varied. When the British took over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they found a large population of educated and literate Africans. German educational efforts in Kamerun and other colonies were also praised by contemporaries. The situation in South West Africa (now Namibia) was different. Unlike in East Africa, where the government played a prominent role in establishing state schools and educating the native population, in South West Africa, the task of educating the natives was largely left to missionary societies with limited government support. While the government did invest significant resources in education for Europeans, establishing a system of state schools and providing more substantial support for missionary schools, these educational policies had lasting effects on South West Africa even after German rule. While other German colonies boasted significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa, “the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate.” Various social, political, and economic factors contributed to this divergent experience in South West Africa. This paper aims to explore these factors, with a focus on new research into the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities towards native Africans. There is a considerable body of literature on education in the German colonial empire, most of which is in German and was written in the early 20th century, during or shortly after the period of German colonial rule. Early works primarily aimed to describe the features of educational systems in these colonies. Later English-language works expanded the discourse through comparative studies of education in the various German colonies and more detailed analyses of specific aspects of education. These studies highlighted significant differences in the educational systems of different colonies. The most prominent work addressing this topic is Cohen's study of education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen compares the educational systems of the two colonies and discusses the factors that explain the differences between them. According to Cohen, the large settler population of South West Africa accounts for many of the distinctive features of the colony's educational system. Compared to Germany's other colonial possessions, South West Africa had a moderately temperate climate, although much of the territory is covered by arid desert. The European population of South West Africa reflected these relatively hospitable conditions. By 1913, nearly 15,000 whites lived in South West Africa, while only 5,336 lived in the colony with the next largest settler population, East Africa.

The classification of popular music has grown over the past 100 years to include so many genres that it is difficult to definitively list them all. Complicating matters, most, if not all, genres—rap, rock, country, jazz, folk, just to name a few—have spawned multiple sub and sub-sub genres within their domain. Arguably, the sub-genre of Heavy Metal rock has become one of the most diverse and expressive genres of all popular music in the past 40 years. It is expressive because it displays a wide range of emotions, although they tend to lean toward the darker side of the spectrum. It is diverse in that quite soon after the beginnings of the genre, people started to realize that it had real flexibility and started to take advantage of it to create their own sub-genre, which then was followed by sub-sub-genres, and the chain continues until today.

Today we have reached a point in the heavy metal movement where there are so many niches of groups that it is hard to determine what exactly heavy metal is. It has grown to incorporate so many themes from other genres, but like everything else, it spawned from somewhere. In order to properly understand the metal music that exists everywhere today, one must first understand what the metal movement is, and why it’s a movement rather than just a genre.

Metal is, in many ways, a movement defined by darkness. Metal can be considered a “music of more”—more bass, more volume, more violence, more theatricality. Less primitivism, more chops; people in metal bands really know how to play their instrument, and it comes through in the music. Metal is also—although it may not come as a surprise—a movement that is heavily drug induced. There was a psychedelic drug boom in the mid-70s that led to people getting crazier, leading to them to make crazy, other-worldly records, using the drugs as a scapegoat for their creation. It possesses many dark, visceral qualities, which was very new to the music scene because a large amount of popular music had qualities that weren’t true to the darker side of the emotional spectrum. Also, later generations of metal have taken some of their influence from the dark, visceral qualities that were so present in the Romantic Era. Lyrics such as the following express the darkness that is such a staple of the movement: (Byrne)

These lyrics from "Helter Skelter" display the darker side of the Beatles. It exhibits an up and down, supposedly that of drugs. This song is considered by some to be one of the first Heavy Metal songs. It was a response to a Rolling Stones song that was also on the heavier, darker side. The Beatles wanted to prove that they could be just as heavy as the Stones, so they put that song on The White Album.

A few decades before the Surrealist artists began painting their dreamlike works, the artist Henri Rousseau was carefully crafting his own dreams, both literally and figuratively. The Dream, a 1910 painting by the famous Post-Impressionist artist, represents not only a woman in awe at the wonders of the land she visits within a dream, but also Rousseau’s own personal dreams and goals as a painter. Since beginning his work, he dreamed of recognition, acceptance, and praise by other artists and art lovers, and found that he was faced with a difficult internal dilemma to achieve this aspiration. The Dream is Henri Rousseau’s work that best reflects his career-long internal struggle: to either conform to or mimic certain styles of painting in order to be accepted by the critical art world he so admired, or to allow himself to be creatively independent and unique, leaving his own path as he went.

Many great thinkers have proposed a close connection between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I believe that at the core, there is a reason for this. As John Keats says in "Ode on a Grecian Urn", "Beauty is truth, truth beauty—That is all / Ye know on Earth, and all ye need to know." Much of what we learn in life comes from education or experience. However, we seem to appreciate ethics and aesthetics, as Keats implies, without formal teaching. Both ethics and aesthetics are attempts to describe, rather than prescribe. Our studies of morality and beauty aim to explain why a piece of art or literature is beautiful, or why an action is moral, rather than offering rules for judging or creating good art or moral behavior.

More precisely, critique of art or morals cannot fully capture their essence. Discussions about the value of da Vinci's Mona Lisa, for instance, may revolve around concepts like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but ultimately, these do not explain why it is good art. Instead, when asked about a favorite work of art or literature, the response often begins with a phrase like, "There's just something about it," followed by a more complex explanation. I believe that both art and morality cannot be fully reduced to a description of their qualities. As Flannery O'Connor says, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said in any other way . . . you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate." No matter how thoroughly we describe the properties of a piece of literature, there is always something transcendent left. I think ethics shares this property. As Wittgenstein put it, "It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. Ethics is transcendental." I suggest that it is this "something," this je ne sais quoi, which is the most powerful attribute of both art and morality, and that this transcendental nature of both ethics and aesthetics provides a connection between them.

I believe that morality and art are closely related because we experience both most powerfully at a noumenal level, using a Kantian term. They affect us at a level that can be felt, but not fully explained. This connection is even stronger with the art of literature. As McKean says, "What most distinguishes literature from other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, like music, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values. . . . Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there."

Modern Germany is considered a strong power, a united country with its distinct culture, from the shadows of the Alps in Munich, to the Baltic Sea city of Kiel, through Cologne on the Rhine River, to the center of Germany, and the Saxon city of Dresden on the Elbe. Due to this unique culture, it is not surprising that Germany, as we know it today, is a result of various sources and tribes.

Germania is the ancestral homeland of the Germans. The origin of the name is disputed among scholars and historians. Tacitus claimed the name came from a Germanic tribe known as the Tungrians, who were previously called Germans before they crossed the Rhine and fought the Gallic forces (Tacitus, 98). Julius Caesar first used the word “Germanus” in his commentary on the Gallic Wars, where he defeated the Gauls and fought with Germanic tribes that often crossed the Rhine under false pretexts. He took this word from the Gauls themselves and used it to distinguish between those he had conquered (the Gauls) and those he had not. While the origin is uncertain, some believe it referred to a neighbor in the Gaulish language. In the first chapter of his first book on these wars, Julius Caesar notes: “Germans, who dwell beyond the Rhine, with whom they (the Gauls) are continually waging war.....They contend with the Germans in almost daily battles.” (Julius Caesar, 50-40 BC) Others claim the meaning comes from the spear they used in warfare, known as a ger (O.E.D., 2010), or perhaps from the Old Irish word garim meaning “to shout”, which indicated the Germans were loud or noisy. (Names of Germany)

The early Roman historian Tacitus recorded in his AD 98 writing “De Origine et situ Germanorum”, which told of the origins of the Germans, that “I should regard (the Germans) as aboriginal, and not mixed at all with other races through immigration or intercourse. For, in former times it was not by land but on shipboard that those who sought to emigrate would arrive.......Who would leave Asia, or Africa, for Italy for Germany, with its wild country, its inclement skies, its sullen manners and aspect, unless indeed it were their home?” (Tacitus, 98)

And who would leave Rome for Germania? Certainly not the Romans, not yet at least. They would send out their conquests into the lands of Germania for goods, and lead the occasional land campaign but in the end they mostly returned back home to their sprawling empire. So as the Germanic tribes began appearing in the middle of the first century, they lived on the borders of the Roman Empire and traded their goods taken from the land, and their skills by serving within the ranks of the Roman army. (Ozment, 2005 pg. 17.)

As I gazed downwards, my mind was blankly absorbing the sight before me. Without emotion, in silence, I analytically observed the scene, acknowledging its details yet keeping them separate from any abstract understanding. My thoughts came and went rapidly, so seamlessly and effortlessly that it seemed I had no personal thoughts, only a fluid experience of the object of my attention. Once, following the advice of an artist I had worked with, I bought a book called "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain." From a young age, I had wanted to learn to draw, and this book teaches everything from understanding a pencil to how the brain interprets lines. One technique it teaches is to frame any picture with a square, simplifying complex scenes into easily digestible compositions. At that moment, staring at the bowl of fruit in front of me, I couldn't visualize this frame. I was too overwhelmed, too awestruck to focus. Picasso had his blue period, Monet loved greenery, and the Italian Renaissance masters displayed a vibrant array of colors. Any pretensions of my artistic prowess dissolved in the face of this scene. My fingers gripped the brush, muscles tensing and releasing as my hand moved through space. I could be creating something extraordinary, but my efforts were futile against the stubborn brown package stuck in the toilet. The offensive object, a bundle of processed animal and plant matter left as a greeting for the janitors at Rite Aid, was my nemesis. A few more flushes, a few more moments of introspection, and my hand reached for the toilet paper, wrapping it around the brush like an oven mitt. Standing upright, bending at the waist, I slowly lowered the brush into the toilet, as if I were a mother preparing the turkey for Thanksgiving....

Teenagers are dying behind the wheel. Several factors coalesce to create this deadly vector of statistics for the youngest American drivers. The National Institutes of Health explain that one facet of the problem is that the teen brain is literally not ready for the hazards of driving. Simple inexperience also lies at the heart of the problem. This inexperience not only causes more fatal accidents, but also a higher rate of vehicle rollover, speeding, and driving off the road.
Teens also fare far worse when they travel with their peers—which anyone with an iota of sense knows they do on a regular basis. The Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center conducted a study that showed the following correlation: between the age of the passenger and the number of traffic accidents occurring.
California and other states have attempted to increase the safety of teen drivers by requiring temporary provisional licenses that limit the hours that teens may drive and prohibit other minors as passengers.
But provisional driver’s licenses are, in my opinion, stopgap measures. The real issue is that—as a group—the youngest drivers are, by all statistical markers, simply not able to adequately handle the risks and responsibilities. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman believes even 18 is too young for a regular driver’s license. USA Today reports that Zuckerman has performed research suggesting a common desire among those under the age of 19-20 to take risks for the sheer thrill of the sensation. It makes sense then, to delay driving at least until the tendency to thrill-seek has begun to level out. If we continue to issue driver’s licenses to young teens, we will not only continue to see deadly accidents happening, but the death toll is likely to reach staggering proportions in the next few years. By 2010, the Baby-Boomer’s babies will be eligible to drive and millions of new teen drivers will ready to hit the road.
Legislation dealing with this issue would be reasonably straightforward. Schools could continue to provide driver’s education classes to begin the learning process for future drivers, but no one under the age of 18 could operate a motor vehicle. A provisional permit could still be issued prior to granting a full driver’s license, and a certain number of practical driver’s training hours would still be required as well. The specific number of hours required could be based on the number of hours already required by the majority of states (in California, for example, that number is currently 6 hours of behind-the-wheel training and 50 hours of practice with an adult.) Because the deadly statistics for teen drivers come from a cross-section of all states, uniform, national legislation on this issue would be a reasonable—and I believe effective—means of protecting teens across the nation.
The legislation I suggest is by no means a novel idea.

Upon browsing through the Library of Congress's collection of early Edison films, I decided to watch all the trick films, of which there were fifteen, spanning from 1895 to 1901. These films typically employ creative editing to create illusions. My film study generally focuses on describing the poetics of the majority of trick films and examining the evolutionary outliers in a few of the later films. Most trick films from the turn of the century are bound within a stage setting, composed within a frontal proscenium, feature no camera movement, and use long and medium shots, adhering strictly to the one shot equals one film method. However, some films from the early 20th century dared to break these rules by incorporating multiple shots.
One commonality among trick films is their filming within a frontal proscenium frame. The camera remains in its proscenium position and does not follow figures or objects. This composition was prevalent in early films, drawing from theater and, for trick films, vaudeville and magic acts. One limitation of using the stage is that figures in trick films generally only move side-to-side and do not walk towards or away from the camera. For instance, in the film Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900), actors enter from the right and move back and forth along the horizontal axis. Even as they exit the frame, the camera does not follow them.
The frontal proscenium style of composition also results in shots being predominantly long shots, with medium shots being less common. Close-ups are never used in any of the trick films from the Edison catalog. This practice borrows from the theater and vaudeville tradition, where the audience sees the entire performance at any given time, framed by the stage borders. Like most early films, actors do not move from the middle ground towards the camera, so close-ups do not occur.
Generally, early trick films follow the pattern that one conceptual shot equals one film. This limits the length of most trick films to about a minute or less, depending on the frames per second used. It also limits the dramatic or narrative usage of trick films; most focus on short vaudeville-style tricks, such as magic, disappearing, and switching acts with little story. However, a trick film's conceptual shot in the viewer's eyes does not necessarily equate to a single physical shot. A single "shot" may be composed of multiple joined shots to create the illusion of apparition or disappearing. Carefully observe The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895), one of the earlier trick films. Upon closer inspection, one can see the moment when the physical shot with Mary's severed "head" begins, despite the entire film being conceptually one shot to the viewer.

John Taylor of Caroline was an early and ardent advocate of Republicanism. Although he was primarily an agriculturalist, his profession and brief political career made him known for his dedication and outspokenness on issues of personal freedom and government. His dedication to an agrarian system was the foundation of almost all his opinions on government. His efforts to preserve and promote the most superior profession, in his view, influenced his arguments on sovereignty, constitutionality, and even the judicial system.

John Taylor believed that the United States had a unique opportunity to establish an ideal system because there were no native traditions to hinder the creators of the government, allowing for the establishment of a system of self-government. He strongly believed in the natural rights of man and the interdependence of these rights—meaning that if one is denied, the others will fail, and their value will be diminished. These rights should therefore be beyond the reach of the government. He argued that the "state of nature" meant those with physical strength and malevolent intelligence would profit, but in a civilization, this should not be the case.

To create this ideal society, Taylor believed a government must account for the inherent good and evil in humans. He had rigid views on dualistic morality. He stated, "As government is exercised by man, all its virtues and vices must be human" (Ibid., pg. 167). He defined good principles as those that protect private property, improve agriculture, and discourage capitalism, believing that a government founded on good principles would function equitably regardless of its administration, which would inevitably be led by avarice and self-interest. He considered self-interest as a natural human trait, but believed it was only considered evil when it led to the creation of sub-societies that lived at the expense of others. A good government was necessary to retain man's natural evil, and even then, it must be closely observed to prevent the addition of bad principles.

Taylor, like many other staunch Republicans of his time, advocated for a strict interpretation of the Constitution. He wanted an extremely limited federal government, with no more rights or powers than explicitly stated in the Constitution. He knew that an extensive federal government was expensive and likely to be despotic. However, he believed that a simple, literal interpretation was dangerous and could easily become corrupt without reference to the intent of the writers. Moreover, he considered the Declaration of Independence the true charter of the United States because it more explicitly describes the country as a union of sovereign states rather than a single nation.

Refers to Figure 17, the third month of the project saw a sharp decline in commuter log submissions. This was somewhat disheartening, but the reason is unclear. The onset of winter in New England may have led to fewer people commuting by bicycle or on foot. Additionally, December marks the end of the fall semester, a busy time for students and faculty finishing schoolwork and processing grades. Filling out the commuter log might have been overlooked. December also brings the holiday season and a month-long break, during which many do not need to come to campus. Classes resume for the spring semester in late January, which may explain the low number of logs for that month. However, nothing explains the low number of submissions in February. One might speculate that such projects typically experience an initial surge of enthusiasm, which may naturally wane. To counter this, we introduced the Carpool Challenge Week in March, a special campaign to boost participation, which led to increased log submissions that month. One of the challenges we faced was maintaining project momentum despite natural decreases in engagement and the impact of holiday and semester breaks on higher education. Another challenge is the deep-seated culture of driving cars, which provides freedom, independence, and flexibility. Thus, offering incentives for alternative commuting modes is essential. We offered gift certificates to local restaurants, coffee shops, massage therapists, an independent bookstore, and even some national chain stores. It would have been interesting to see if larger prizes, such as bicycles or hybrid/electric cars, could have further boosted participation. Increasing the value of prizes over time might have helped. The gift cards were sufficient at the start, but announcing additional larger prizes could have increased participation and engagement.

An ETF (exchange-traded fund) is a type of security that tracks an index, commodity, or basket of assets like an index fund, but it trades like a stock on an exchange. An ETF offers the diversification of an index fund and the benefits of single stock ownership, such as short selling, buying on margin, and purchasing as few as one share in a single transaction. However, ETFs have lower expense ratios than most mutual funds. On the downside, you have to pay a commission for any ETF trade, just like a stock order. Another advantage of ETFs is the wide range of funds available. While these benefits are clear, it's always wise for an informed investor to assess whether these benefits, such as diversification, actually exist to the stated extent. For this analysis, we will examine the ETF IHF and compare it to its top 10 holdings to determine if the benefits of owning a single ETF are close to those of a diversified portfolio of the ten stocks, and whether there are better stock combinations that could provide a more optimal risk-return ratio.

To evaluate the ETF, it would be impractical to include all holdings, so we will only consider the top 10 holdings, which make up 63.58% of the ETF's assets. Below are the top 10 holdings and their respective percentages of total assets.

To estimate how well these ten stocks represent the ETF IHF as a whole, we can use the current percentage of assets, normalized to 100%, to calculate their contributions to a portfolio's Beta and Return if the portfolio consisted of these 10 stocks in the proportion held by the ETF. The calculations of Beta and Return are included in the chart below.

From the chart, it is evident that a portfolio containing only the top 10 holdings would have a return 6.11% higher than the ETF, a 16% increase in returns. It also shows that the Beta of the top 10 holdings is 0.12 lower than the ETF's overall Beta. Based on these results, it appears that a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings could provide higher returns with lower risk. However, the means of the two portfolios may not be statistically different from each other.

To determine if these portfolios are statistically different, we will calculate the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks and normalize it to 100% to compare their accumulated standard deviation with that of the ETF IHF.

Dream-land is one of Edgar Allan Poe's self-proclaimed better poems. In "Dream-land" Poe uses the term "Thulé" in lines 6 and 56 which Mabbott traces back to Virgil. Virgil used the term in reference to an island north of Britain which the Greeks considered the edge of the known world. It is certain that Virgil did use the term however there is a more current source to which some credit must be given. Poe was very interested in German authors.

This quote is important because it shows Poe’s familiarity with Goethe’s writing. Karl J. Arndt, in his book Poe’s Politian and Goethe’s Mignon, comments on the similarity of their two poems drawing the conclusion that Poe was imitating Goethe.

The Oxford Companion to English Literature says of Goethe was a celebrated writer of the poetic drama Faust which was published in two parts the first in 1808 and the second in the year of Goethe’s death 1832. Within the poetic verse of Faust’s second part lies a short poem titled “The King of Thulé”.  The poem is about a king whose wife dies after she gives him the gift of a goblet. After his wife passes he begins drinking heavily and crying from the memory of his dead queen. He then decides it is his time to die and gives his possessions to his children save for the goblet. He then walks to a cliff, throws the goblet into the ocean, closes his eyes, and dies. The demeanor of the King of Thule and the description of the king in Dream-Land are very similar, maybe a dark doppelganger of Poe’s loss and crutch of drinking. Faust was also composed into a romantic drama by H P Grattan in 1842, which was less than one year prior to Poe’s use of the term Thule in “The Pit and the Pendulum”.

Poe references Thule twice in his collected writings. Once Poe references “ultma Thule” in The Pit and the Pendulum but he uses this phrase in “Dream-Land” twice, as book ends for the poem. “The King of Thule” and “Dream-Land” can be read as companion pieces. In “Dream-Land” the speaker says. He then describes the landscape of Thule and how it is dark, lonely, he is haunted by dead friends, and he sees a shaded world without color. All of these scenes would be read into “The King of Thule” by Goethe as he has just lost his wife, he is lonely, and he has lost his will to rule or even live. The entire poem is a description as though the speaker has stepped into Goethe’s poem.

Goethe was a significant author who Poe would have known if for no other reason then his respect for Tennyson. Poe had this to say when asked if he admired Tennyson. Aside from the connection to Tennyson Poe would have been exposed to Goethe’s work in the many reproductions that were taking place after the original publication.

Under California law, could a customer injured after slipping and falling on an applesauce spill in a grocery store be awarded punitive damages by showing the store manager acted with malice because he was informed twice of the spill and failed to have it cleaned for a half-hour because he was eating dinner?

A judge is not likely to summarily dismiss Jennifer Palmer’s punitive damage claim. To state a claim that an award of punitive damages is justified, a plaintiff must present evidence that the defendant’s actions were committed with a willful and conscious disregard for the probable harm that would result from the conduct, as well as showing that the conduct was despicable. Palmer will be able to argue that Martin should have known the probable harm of not cleaning a spill because multiple D&D customers were injured from slipping in the months prior to Palmer’s accident; and despite this knowledge he still failed to have the spill cleaned. Palmer’s argument that Martin’s actions were despicable are less persuasive, but are still reasonable given the facts that six slip-and-fall incidents had occurred in 2009 and Martin still failed to take appropriate actions to maintain the safety of his store.

On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 pm, Rich Wayne, an employee of D&D Markets, informed his manager, Paul Martin, that there was an applesauce spill in an aisle. Martin told Wayne that he was on dinner break and “didn’t have time to deal with customer complaints.” At 5:15 pm, another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, also notified Mr. Martin of the spill, and Martin responded the same way. At 5:30 pm on the thirteenth, the plaintiff, Jennifer Palmer, slipped and fell on the spill and sustained a serious back injury. Prior to Palmer’s accident, five different slip-and-fall incidents had been reported at D&D’s in the year 2009. Palmer is now suing D&D for compensatory and punitive damages related to her injury, and we are examining whether to file a motion for partial summary judgment against the punitive damage claim.

In California, a plaintiff can recover punitive damages for a breach of an obligation not arising out of a contract if the defendant acted with “oppression, fraud or malice.” Cal. Civ. Code, § 3294(a) (Lexis 2010). The statute defines malice as conduct that intended to cause harm, or absent intent, the conduct must be “despicable” and committed with “a willful and conscious disregard of the rights or safety of others.” id. at § 3294c(1). Courts have characterized conduct as malicious when committed with a conscious disregard of the plaintiff’s rights when the defendant “was aware of the probable dangerous consequences of his conduct, and that he willfully and deliberately failed to avoid those consequences.” Taylor v. Super. Ct. of Los Angeles Co., 598 P. 2d 853, 856 (Cal. 1979).

Almost four years ago, I studied Islam at CBC. One of the main topics of heated discussion in the class was whether or not Islam is a hostile religion. I believe that the question is even more relevant today than ever before. Looking back on events since 9/11, I personally observed that the mass media's view of Islam and extremists changed from being hostile to an extreme form of tolerance in America. I don’t think in 2001 we could have had a presidential candidate named Barack Obama, who had an obvious Muslim background.

The Biography of the Prophet is intriguing to me because, based on my knowledge of the history of Muhammad, the biography contradicts the personality of Muhammad. From what I know and learned in the past, I thought that Muhammad forced converts to Islam. He would conquer and take over tribes and then force them to adopt the Islamic religion. However, according to the biography, Muhammad was depicted as a sort of martyr, who was misunderstood and even humbled himself to others. After that, people came to see the 'truth' in his teachings and sought him out.

Additionally, there are some uncanny similarities between Jesus' ministries and the 'miracles' of Muhammad. The most obvious one is when he took mutton and milk and multiplied them to feed more than forty men. This style of writing makes me believe that the authors wanted Muhammad to be perceived as a humble prophet, who did not need to prove anything, but simply lived in truth and miracles. This sort of fallacy is the worst because it diminishes the miracle and life of Jesus Christ. To me, it's like they are stealing and trying to take credit for Jesus' life and personhood through Muhammad.

There are also many stories in the biography that make it seem like one of their agendas is to provide proof of 'witness' or how people 'voluntarily' converted to Islam. However, the problem is that many of the stories are at least from a third-party perspective. That is, in the story, the author illustrates that he heard from so-and-so who heard from so-and-so, and so on. I didn’t like this much because although their intention was to provide proof of the truth of the stories, I thought it diminished the stories and made them seem even more suspicious.

I think the thing that bothers me most about this work is that they try to elevate and glorify Muhammad as a godly, humble, endearing, wise, and gentle man. However, history contradicts the idea that Muhammad was a gentle and humble man, and I can’t help but wonder if Muslims today know the true history behind Muhammad's rise to power.

The teachings of Jesus and the beliefs he held during his lifetime were immediately left behind in the development of Christian thought that moved forward after his life. If we look at this history in broad strokes, we see a trend of Christianity straying farther and farther from its origin. It seems that today’s world shows an ever-growing awareness and an unprecedented progressive tendency. While traditional people remain and will resist any kind of thinking beyond what was taught to them, this portion of the population may not be prominent enough to influence the whole. Among Christians, a historical awareness will grow immensely in future years. A yearning will spread, to distinguish the doctrines that were added into Christianity over time from the actual intent of the religion’s namesake. It may take decades or even centuries, but the outcome will be inevitable: There will be a great reversal in the trend of Christian history. There will be a progression back to its original form. A movement will grow in numbers that will remove layers of doctrine, one after the other, just as if the clock started moving backward, until nothing is left except a conception of what Jesus introduced to humanity on behalf of God, before any other thinkers made such claims. When this trend sweeps through the United States and Europe, influencing masses in its wake to worship as if we were living at the time of Jesus, following only his ideas, the church as an institution will remain strong to lead the way. However, because the theological clock will have moved backward, the extreme proliferation of diversity in Christendom will reverse into more and more uniformity of belief and practice. Between regions, between denominations, between divisions of every kind, we will see instead of differences, increasing similarities. Human history is filled with great reversions. Just one example is how Christians were at one time persecuted, shunned and killed by the Roman Empire. But later that empire became a Christian institution. Our country has gone from African-American slavery to African-American leadership. The great reversion coming in our future will play itself out in the arena of the Christian religion, undoing history in search of the source, and undoing diversity in the process. It is crucial to note that part of what will make this process possible will be a method of reading Jesus’ words as metaphorical, and not as literal statements. So what is it that happened since Jesus’ lifetime?

If we look far enough back into history, we find only Judaism, the theological beginning for the Christian religion. Monotheism, the perception of a divinely revealed religion, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures, were all at the core of the religion by the time the Romans assumed control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. The Jewish population did not share one spirit. They divided into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots and a majority of common people.

I believe that The Jungle illustrates how people, at their core, are inherently selfish and self-centered. They seek only to improve their own lives and never consider those less fortunate than themselves. The novel demonstrates this in various ways. For instance, factory owners and managers are solely focused on expanding their businesses and increasing profits, disregarding anyone or anything that stands in their way or is harmed by their progress. Upton Sinclair's description of the factories, "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world," highlights the destructive impact of this pollution. Sinclair shows that the owners have no regard for the people or animals affected by the smog or the waste from the thousands of pens in Packingtown.

The owners and managers also showed no concern for their employees, who they exploited to enrich themselves. They would do whatever it took to save a penny, "So from the top to bottom the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere about it, there is no place in it where a man counted for anything against a dollar." They forced workers to labor long hours and could dismiss them suddenly without notice or compensation. During the time The Jungle was set, there were few, if any, laws protecting workers' safety or well-being. This allowed the managers and owners to treat their employees harshly, pushing them to work in dangerous conditions. The book doesn't explicitly state this, but those who died from working in Packingtown were expected to endure the horrific conditions both at the factories and in the surrounding area. There were no agencies or organizations to provide information or assistance to workers. Some unions were formed, but they often did more harm than good, profiting from the workers' misery. The workers were so maltreated and trapped in the system that they were likened to slaves, "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery."

Many authors employ various techniques to convey a particular feeling or attitude towards significant subjects. Some methods are more effective than others. In his novel The Great Gatsby, F. Scott Fitzgerald uses many such techniques. He might combine an adjective and a noun in an unusual way to create a certain atmosphere around a subject, or he might invest a symbol with meaning and then use it for the same purpose. Fitzgerald employs this latter technique with various colors, including gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink. In The Great Gatsby, Fitzgerald assigns specific meanings to colors, particularly white/gray and red/pink, which he then uses to remind readers of feelings related to important objects.

Fitzgerald's portrayal of white/gray signifies uniformity, with white representing a higher social status and gray indicating something older and faded. He establishes this association early in the novel through consistent use of these colors. Daisy and Jordan are frequently described as being "in white” (8), for instance, everyone wears white at Gatsby's party, Tom wears a white shirt when he meets Myrtle, and Catherine is described as “powdered milky white” (30). The only exceptions are when Nick attends Gatsby's party, where the halls are adorned with primary colors (40). Fitzgerald further reinforces this color association by applying white/gray to myriad everyday subjects: Nick’s commute takes him through the “white chasms of lower New York” (56), names of people at Gatsby's parties appear as “gray names” (61) in Nick’s notes, Catherine's apartment is “one slice in a long white cake of apartment-houses” (28), and he describes ordinary people and places in white or gray, such as Jordan and Daisy’s shared “white girlhood” (19), the “gray cars” and “gray land” (23) in the valley of ashes, an “Italian child” (26) in a railroad car who is “gray,” and a “gray old man” (27) selling dogs.

After building enough significance around white/gray, Fitzgerald employs them to signify unimportance or uniformity in relation to certain subjects. This use of colors to convey meaning begins with Daisy. After an extended period without significant use of white/gray, Daisy is described as “dressed in white” in “a little white roadster” (74), which begins to diminish her character and portrays her more as a uniform object, something Gatsby longs for. Fitzgerald continues this technique around Daisy to emphasize her uniformity, such as the “gray haze of Daisy’s fur collar” (18) and her wearing a white dress (115) before Tom and Gatsby’s encounter.

San Diego County is highly productive in agriculture due to its mild and sunny climate. Common crops include tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits such as peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There is a strong market for organic community supported agriculture in the San Diego area, with many local organizations having long waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also in high demand. Many organic farms offer tours and recreational activities like hiking and birdwatching. This type of operation can help landowners benefit from government programs while improving habitat and providing additional income through tours and educational programs.

Besides filling a potentially profitable niche market, organic farming often leads to greater biodiversity in plants and wildlife due to the absence of chemicals. However, organic farming has higher costs compared to conventional farming. It requires more labor and management to control pests and weeds without chemicals, and there are often higher losses. Small organic farms lack the efficiency of large-scale operations. Additionally, practices beneficial to wildlife, such as planting cover crops and strategic grazing, can involve higher labor costs. Therefore, landowners may seek financial assistance or expertise to maximize profits and habitat quality.

The chosen parcel is adjacent to the town of Potrero in unincorporated San Diego County, California. It is 160 acres of chaparral, non-native Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland near the Cleveland National Forest. This land is located in the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion under the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan, which is currently under review. The plan considers over a hundred plant and animal species, including endangered ones like the Stephens’ kangaroo rat, mountain yellow-legged frog, several butterfly species, and the California gnatcatcher. Other species are declining and may soon be listed, such as burrowing owls.

This area was home to Native Americans for centuries before being settled by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800s. This land was part of an original homestead patent and was likely used for grazing and/or wood production for many years. I researched real estate websites and government programs to find cost-mitigating options for a small farmer looking to preserve wildlife-friendly operations. As a model, I identified an organic farm in the same area.

Culture plays a significant role in any negotiation. Culture can be defined by what it is not as much as what it actually is and what it signifies. Culture is not homogeneous, nor is it a specific thing. It is also not singular or uniform. Statements such as “all Russians are stubborn” or “all Japanese are accommodating,” are inherently broad and overly simplistic. While the understanding of a culture’s generalizations is appropriate, it is much more productive for a negotiator to understand the significance of a culture to the matter at hand, and how that culture’s attitude can and will affect the table talks. When one approaches a foreign culture, one experiences it in a way that is relatable to his own culture, and comparisons necessarily arise. Attempting to understand a foreign culture or mindset can involve anything from studying its history to realizing its prejudices. Rather than judging or attempting to change a culture, one must simply accept it for what it is, and work within its boundaries, especially within the scope of negotiation, and most especially if one comes to the table with a weaker bargaining position. Likewise, if a negotiator finds himself on “away” territory, a respect for traditions and beliefs can only help in getting over any cultural barriers and move the negotiation forward. It is important to note that culture does not necessarily limit itself to a national/international dichotomy. Most companies within a given nation establish their own corporate culture. For instance, a corporate culture might emphasize long hours in the office or a more relaxed schedule. Evidence of a corporate culture can be seen in employee dress codes, in communication style (direct v. indirect communication, delegation of duties), and hiring practices. Some companies encourage philanthropy at any level from employees, others restrict it to “company approved” charities or fundraisers. One need only look at the differences in American corporate culture from company to company (and indeed, intra-company diversity exists even from region to region, urban to suburban environments included) to appreciate the diversity of thought that can reside within a particular societal culture. Certain cultures are not nearly as stratified as American culture, and may appear more uniform to an outsider, but a similar exterior is simply a sign to dig deeper. Values are even more important to understand, because they provide the why of a culture. If saving face or communal harmony are valued within a culture, it is certain that a negotiator will not publicly shame his company or his superior in order to succeed at the negotiation table. Likewise, a negotiator from a culture which gives greater weight to a hard-driven bargain will not necessarily be driven to settle at the earliest opportunity. Taking these generalities into consideration is important before one gets to the negotiating table. However, a negotiator is well-served to learn something about his opponent on a personal level in order to make the negotiation effective.

“The fool hath said in his heart, ‘There is no God.’” This phrase first appears in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible, and is the opening of St. Anselm’s argument regarding the existence of God. This belief is also shared by another author we will discuss, Thomas Aquinas. Since both arguments are in defense of the same concept, we must, for the sake of brevity, assume they are both correct in their belief in the existence of God, specifically the God of the Bible. To allow for a God-type figure that may not resemble the one our two authors believe in would not permit us to appropriately compare their arguments, as they are essentially in defense of one specific concept of God. That being said, I would suggest that while each of them presents valid points, neither truly provides a comprehensive basis for belief in God.

To illustrate this point, let’s first examine St. Anselm’s basic argument. Anselm’s passage reflects a path of gaining understanding through faith, looking within oneself to find proof of God. He explains that because God exists within our understanding, we cannot effectively conceive his nonexistence. While this concept, when put into words, can be tedious and at times unclear, the basic idea is that the proof of God lies within one’s own mind. St. Anselm suggests that we needn’t go beyond the confines of our own soul to find truth about God; the existence of this being is true simply by examining what we inherently know to be true within our minds. Foreign evidence is presumably unnecessary. This concept of accepting something for which there is not irrefutable empirical evidence is often referred to within Christian texts as faith.

This idea is very different from that held by St. Thomas Aquinas. Aquinas suggests that the existence of God can be proven entirely through reason and empirical evidence, with no need for faith of any kind. Such an idea would be beneficial in evangelism, an important element of Christianity, because it would enable the recruitment of new converts without any dependency on their willingness to accept something that cannot be proven. They could instead be persuaded by logic alone. St. Thomas elaborates on five different logical arguments supporting the existence of God: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. In each, he essentially demonstrates that the proof of God lies in the logical necessity for God. If you are told that you are missing one puzzle piece, and assemble the rest of the puzzle, logic dictates that you can know of the features and the existence of the missing piece without having to see it.

Sometimes in the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince who would later be known as the Buddha was born. Throughout his life, he renounced the world, attained enlightenment, and his teachings gave rise to Buddhism—the most traditional form of which is known as Theravada Buddhism. The religion has existed for approximately 2500 years, and it has undergone significant changes since the Buddha's lifetime. This can be seen in various ways, such as in the Theravada nation of Sri Lanka, where the annual water-cutting ceremony is held. Both monks and laypeople participate in this event, which holds religious significance despite the Buddha never teaching about such a ceremony. These differences extend from superficial traditions to the core soteriological beliefs of the religion. The Theravada Buddhist community, from both the monastic and lay perspectives, has had to adapt its doctrinal principles over time due to both external and internal influences, as well as both hostile and benign factors.

This discussion will frequently use several key terms. The distinction between internal and external forces will be important. Here, an internal force refers to any influence stemming from members of the Buddhist community, regardless of their monastic status. An external force refers to any influence from non-Buddhists. A hostile force is any influence that harms or intends to harm the Buddhist community, driven by a negative perception of Buddhism. A benign force is any influence that does not wish to harm or help the Buddhist community, but may have unintended consequences.

First, it is crucial to understand the fundamental principles of the religion—the core tenets of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists take refuge in the three jewels: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is essentially the Tripitaka, the three baskets of Buddhist texts. The Sutta Pitaka contains all the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka contains the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka comprises the metaphysical components of Buddhism. These include concepts like Anatta (no self), Dukkha (inherent suffering), and Anicca (impermanence). Only by recognizing these concepts can one escape Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth, which is ongoing. Along with the escape from Sansara, lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion) also cease when one attains enlightenment. The Vinaya Pitaka outlines rules for life, including the five precepts for laypeople (I shall not kill, I shall not lie, I shall not steal, I shall not engage in sexual misconduct, and I shall not consume intoxicating substances) and numerous disciplinary rules for monks. The most fundamental doctrinal notion in Buddhism is the Four Noble Truths. First, life is suffering (Dukkha). Second, attachment causes suffering. Third, suffering can be overcome.

The United States of America and Mexico are an example of two nations that once had a long-standing rivalry that lasted for 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. (Diehl and Goerts 2000, p. 145). The peak of this rivalry was the Mexican-American War in 1846-1848, in which the United States defeated Mexico and gained Texas and the American Southwest as new territories. There were numerous other conflicts between the two nations until just before World War I. The rivalry began due to disputes over key issues such as religion, culture, and tradition, as well as material interests (Schmitt 1974, p. 30-31). This is similar to many other nations with enduring rivalries with their neighbors. Nations sharing a border often have conflicting interests that lead to rival positions. The United States and Mexico are not unlike other enduring rivalries between border-sharing nations. David M. Pletcher (1977) stated, “Only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting overarching American diplomatic problems” (p. 41). Indeed, these two nations are geographically close to the United States and have historically been rivals, while other Latin American nations have enjoyed or continue to enjoy good relations with the United States. Religious issues created a rift between the two nations, a problem faced by many nations throughout history. Sally Frahm (2001) noted, “If in the twentieth century Americans were opposed to fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries they were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy” (p. 86). The rivalry between the United States and Mexico was also ideological, but it was not based on political structure; rather, it was centered on religious preferences. This distrust was inherited from the historic rivalry between the English and Spanish, making it a major obstacle in establishing friendly foreign relations between the United States and Mexico. Diehl and Goerts (2000) list 17 disputes between Mexico and the United States during this 57-year rivalry period. Most of these disputes were territorial issues related to border raids from Mexican territory and other frontier problems. Border raids by bandits and outlaws from American border towns were a significant concern until the United States and Mexico both applied military force along their borders (Schmitt 1974, p. 97). Schmitt (1974) explains that the rivalry began to diminish as “Mexico became clearly dependent on the United States in a substantial way” (p. 109) and finally ended as American ambitions “changed from territorial expansion to economic intervention into Mexico” (p. 110) in the late 19th century.
